04334nam a22005415i 9780773597440DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735974407 a10.1515/97807735974402doi  a(DE-B1597)655740  a(OCoLC)910775893  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0420202bisacsh04a320.509qOCoLC223/eng/20230216  aMC 7000qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122415:1 aCochrane, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLeft and Right :bThe Small World of Political Ideas /cChristopher Cochrane. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource :b28 figures, 1 photo, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Urban Governance ;v300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe “Meaning” of Left and Right -- tIdeology, Dimensionality, and Asymmetry -- tThe Structure and Content of Left / Right Differences -- tLeft / Right Positions and Polarization -- tLeft / Right Persistence and Evolution -- tCitizens' Left / Right Orientations -- tThe Rise of Left / Right in Canadian Politics -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe words "left" and "right" often signal a political divide in debates about topics as diverse as abortion, capital punishment, gun control, social welfare, taxation, immigration, and the environment. Despite claims that political polarization is in decline, its persistence suggests that it is inherent to our society. At the same time, variations in the perception of each side indicate that these labels do not fully capture the reality of ideological disagreement. In Left and Right, Christopher Cochrane traces the origins of this political language to the very nature of ideology. What is ideology, what does it look like, and how does it manifest itself in patterns of political disagreement in Western democracies? Drawing on five decades of evidence from political scientists, including public opinion surveys, elite surveys, and content analysis of political party election platforms, Cochrane employs a new method to analyze the structure and evolution of the left/right divide in twenty-one Western countries since 1945. He then delves into the central argument of the book - that the language of left and right describes a meaningful, perceptible, and quantifiable pattern of political disagreement that has persisted over time and around the world. Calling for an adjustment to the way we view Canadian politics, Left and Right opens a window into the world of political ideologies - a world we see every day, but rarely analyze, define, or agree on.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRight and left (Political science)xHistoryy20th century. 0aRight and left (Political science)xHistoryy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Conservatism & Liberalism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773597440?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773597440423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773597440/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles